When a patient presents with a history of one or more hypomanic episodes and one or more depressive episodes that meet the criteria for a [[major depressive episode]], [[bipolar II disorder]] is diagnosed. If the depressive episodes are routinely during the winter and the hypomania presents in the spring/summer it is possible that the person may be diagnosed with [[Seasonal Affective Disorder]] instead of bipolar II disorder.<ref>
