==Treatment==
{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2011}}
Medications typically prescribed for hypomania include [[mood stabilizers]] such as [[valproic acid]] and [[lithium carbonate]] as well as [[atypical antipsychotics]] such as [[olanzapine]] and [[quetiapine]].

==Notable individuals with hypomanic symptoms==
For more information, please see [[List of people affected by bipolar disorder]].

[[John Gartner]]'s book ''The Hypomanic Edge''<ref name="Hypomanic Edge">''The Hypomanic Edge: The Link Between (A Little) Craziness and (A Lot of) Success in America'', Gartner, John D. (Simon & Schuster, New York, 2005) http://hypomanicedge.com</ref> claims notable people including [[Christopher Columbus]], [[Alexander Hamilton]], [[Andrew Carnegie]], and [[Louis B. Mayer]] owe their innovation and drive, as well as their eccentricities, to hypomanic temperaments.{{Page needed|date=February 2009}}  Gartner suggests that the constructive behaviors associated with hypomania may contribute to bipolar disorder's evolutionary survival.{{Page needed|date=February 2009}} Critics charge that Gartner vastly overstates his case, however.<ref name="Review of of Hypomanic Edge" >E.g. review by Nassir Ghaemi, M.D., M.A., M.P.H. at [http://www.mentalhelp.net/poc/view_doc.php?id=2913&type=book&cn=4 Mentalhealth.net].</ref>
Following his analysis includes people like [[Theodore Roosevelt]], [[Henry Ford]], [[Steve Jobs]], [[Bill Clinton]],<ref>http://us.macmillan.com/insearchofbillclinton/JohnGartner</ref> [[Charlie Sheen]],<ref>http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-roving-psychologist/201103/charlie-sheen-hypomanias-poster-boy</ref> [[Rahm Emanuel]]<ref>http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-roving-psychologist/200908/the-amazing-emanuel-brothers</ref> and [[Mark Zuckerberg]].<ref>www.nytimes.com/2010/09/19/business/19entre.html</ref>

